Since the data has an high imbalance between non-fradulent and fradualent transactions,we need to fix that so that the models have a better chance in predicting accurately. Over sampling, undersampling or even the SMOTE techniques can be used to address this issue. Once the trasactions can be explores more closely, a technique will be choosen.

In the meanwhile, since the dataset source is from actual bank/finacial institute most of the features are unknown except for time and amount which can be used for minimal data exploration. The time features is given in minutes, but by converting it to hours we can better examine when the transactions occured and also create a cleaner visual represetation. In addition to time, the amount for each trasaction done can also be examined to see if the amounts and the time of the trasactions have any kind of significance to fradualent cases in the dataset.

#IQR to identify outliers to remove 

Q1 = df['Amount'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df['Amount'].quantile(0.75)

IQR = Q3 - Q1

lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

out = df[(df['Amount'] < lower_bound) | (df['Amount'] > upper_bound)]

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4), dpi=80)
sns.boxplot(x=out['Amount'], color='red')
plt.title('Distribution of Amount with Outliers')
plt.show()

The SMOTE technique is used to balance the data so that the predictions can be more efficent. With the technique now both classes are even. Now it is time to utilize Non-supervised learning to see how well the data can be used to predict to begin with basic differntations between the classes. The PCA and K means are emplyed to explore this below, to which seems to be successful as two groups were accurately identified.

from sklearn.metrics import recall_score

# Evaluate models
def evaluate_model(y_true, y_pred, model_name):
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)
    precision = precision_score(y_true, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_true, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(y_true, y_pred)

    print(f"Metrics for {model_name}:")
    print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
    print(f"Precision: {precision:.4f}")
    print(f"Recall: {recall:.4f}")
    print(f"F1 Score: {f1:.4f}")
    print()

evaluate_model(y_test, y_test_pred , "Random Forest")
evaluate_model(y_test, y_pred_dt, "Decision Tree")

print("\nClassification Report RF:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_test_pred))
print("\nClassification Report DT:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred_dt))

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Function to plot confusion matrix
def plot_confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, model_name, ax):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", cbar=False,
                xticklabels=['Predicted 0', 'Predicted 1'],
                yticklabels=['Actual 0', 'Actual 1'], ax=ax)
    ax.set_title(f'Confusion Matrix - {model_name}')
    ax.set_xlabel('Predicted')
    ax.set_ylabel('Actual')

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 5))

#Plot Confusion Matrix 
plot_confusion_matrix(y_test, y_test_pred, "Random Forest", axes[0])
plot_confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_dt, "Decision Tree", axes[1])

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

def plot_confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, model_name):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    plt.figure(figsize=(4, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", cbar=False,
                xticklabels=['Predicted 0', 'Predicted 1'],
                yticklabels=['Actual 0', 'Actual 1'])
    plt.title(f'Confusion Matrix - {model_name}')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot_confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, model_name):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    plt.figure(figsize=(4, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", cbar=False,
                xticklabels=['Predicted 0', 'Predicted 1'],
                yticklabels=['Actual 0', 'Actual 1'])
    plt.title(f'Confusion Matrix - {model_name}')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.show()

model_name = "Your Model Name"
plot_confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred, model_name)
print("\nClassification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, roc_curve, auc, precision_recall_curve

def plot_roc_pr_curves(y_true, y_pred_proba, model_name):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

    # ROC Curve
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_true, y_pred_proba)
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange', lw=2, label='ROC curve (area = {:.2f})'.format(auc(fpr, tpr)))
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('ROC Curve (Test Set)')
    plt.legend(loc='lower right')

    # Precision-Recall Curve
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_true, y_pred_proba)
    plt.plot(recall, precision, color='blue', lw=2, label='Precision-Recall curve (area = {:.2f})'.format(auc(recall, precision)))
    plt.xlabel('Recall')
    plt.ylabel('Precision')
    plt.title('Precision-Recall Curve (Test Set)')
    plt.legend(loc='upper right')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.suptitle(f'Model Evaluation - {model_name}', y=1.02)
    plt.show()

model_name = "Your Model Name"
plot_roc_pr_curves(y_test, model.predict(X_test), model_name)
print("\nClassification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
